SIMPLE: mock
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mock
<hw>Mock</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Mocked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mocking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>moquer</ets>, of
uncertain origin; cf. OD. <ets>mocken</ets> to mumble, G.
<ets>mucken</ets>, OSw. <ets>mucka</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
imitate; to mimic; esp., to mimic in sport, contempt, or derision; to
deride by mimicry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To see the life as lively <qex>mocked</qex> as ever⟦br⟧
Still sleep <qex>mocked</qex> death.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mocking</qex> marriage with a dame of France.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To treat with scorn or contempt; to
deride.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Elijah <qex>mocked</qex> them, and said, Cry aloud.</q> <rj><qau>1
Kings xviii. 27.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let not ambition <qex>mock</qex> their useful toil.</q>
<rj><qau>Gray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To disappoint the hopes of; to deceive; to
tantalize; <as>as, to <ex>mock</ex> expectation</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou hast <qex>mocked</qex> me, and told me lies.</q>
<rj><qau>Judg. xvi. 13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He will not . . . ⟦br⟧
<qex>Mock</qex> us with his blest sight, then snatch him hence.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To deride; ridicule; taunt; jeer; tantalize;
disappoint. See <er>Deride</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mock</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mock
<hw>Mock</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make sport in contempt or in
jest; to speak in a scornful or jeering manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When thou <qex>mockest</qex>, shall no man make thee ashamed?</q>
<rj><qau>Job xi. 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She had <qex>mocked</qex> at his proposal.</q>
<rj><qau>Froude.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mock</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mock
<hw>Mock</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An act of ridicule or
derision; a scornful or contemptuous act or speech; a sneer; a jibe; a
jeer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fools make a <qex>mock</qex> at sin.</q> <rj><qau>Prov. xiv.
9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Imitation; mimicry.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Crashaw.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mock</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Mock
<hw>Mock</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Imitating reality, but not real;
false; counterfeit; assumed; sham.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That superior greatness and <qex>mock</qex> majesty.</q>
<rj><qau>Spectator.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mock bishop's weed</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a
genus of slender umbelliferous herbs (<gen>Discopleura</gen>) growing in
wet places.</cd> -- <col><b>Mock heroic</b></col>, <cd>burlesquing the
heroic; <as>as, a <ex>mock heroic</ex> poem</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mock
lead</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Blende</er> (<sd>a</sd>).</cd> --
<col><b>Mock nightingale</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the European
blackcap.</cd> -- <col><b>Mock orange</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a
genus of American and Asiatic shrubs (<gen>Philadelphus</gen>), with
showy white flowers in panicled cymes. <spn>Philadelphus
coronarius</spn>, from Asia, has fragrant flowers; the American kinds
are nearly scentless.</cd> -- <col><b>Mock sun</b></col>. <cd>See
<er>Parhelion</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mock turtle soup</b></col>, <cd>a
soup made of calf's head, veal, or other meat, and condiments, in
imitation of green turtle soup.</cd> -- <col><b>Mock velvet</b></col>,
<cd>a fabric made in imitation of velvet. See
<er>Mockado</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mockable</ent>⟦br⟧
